{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:47:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:47:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17973"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17973"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.79,0.15,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10687"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6878"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7197"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24991"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) passes through a particular gland on its way to cutaneous innervation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Through which one of the following glands does it pass?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lacrimal","Parotid","Submandibular","Sublingual","Thyroid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) passes between the superficial and deep lobes of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eparotid\u003C/strong\u003E gland, where it forms a plexus known as the parotid plexus. From this plexus, five terminal branches arise: temporal, zygomatic, buccal, marginal mandibular, and cervical. These branches are responsible for innervating the muscles of facial expression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esublingual\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmandibular\u003C/strong\u003E glands are other salivary glands but are not pierced by the facial nerve. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elacrimal\u003C/strong\u003E glands are not related to the path of the facial nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) passes through the parotid gland, where it forms a plexus and gives rise to five terminal branches.","The five terminal branches of the facial nerve are temporal, zygomatic, buccal, marginal mandibular, and cervical.","The parotid gland is the largest of the salivary glands and is located near the ear."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17973"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58739","links":{"self":"https://ap